{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480426"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:42:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:42:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"50"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"50","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/50"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.05,0.28,0.55,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"50"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52779"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"50","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/50"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"50"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38160"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"128"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1911"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1768"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2109"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2372"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35975"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37884"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41969"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42955"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52779","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52779"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old man presents to his general practice with a three-day history of constant pleuritic chest pain, shortness of breath, nausea, and vomiting. The chest pain is worse when recumbent. He reports an additional one-week history of coryzal symptoms. He has a medical history of atrial fibrillation and chronic kidney disease for consideration of haemodialysis in the near future.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his blood pressure 95/60mmHg, pulse rate 58/min, temperature is 37.9\u00baC, respiratory rate 20/min and SpO2 90% on room air. His JVP is 5cm. There are bibasal crepitations to the mid zones of the chest and his heart sounds are soft. A pericardial friction rub is auscultated over the midaxillary region. There is peripheral oedema to the mid-calves.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn ECG shows sinus bradycardia with small QRS complexes. His biochemistry is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely aetiology for the patient\u0027s presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute coronary syndrome","Antiarrhythmic medications","Viral respiratory illness","Uraemia","Bacterial pneumonia"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis man\u0027s current and acute problem is pericarditis. This diagnosis would explain his pleuritic chest pain and its worsening nature when he lies flat. The pericardial friction rub adds further evidence, and there is probably a pericardial effusion with a resulting cardiac tamponade to explain the hypotension, reduced heart sounds, elevated JVP and dependent oedema. The ECG changes would fit with cardiac tamponade.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere are many causes of pericarditis. The aetiology that best fits the patient\u0027s profile and presentation is\u003Cstrong\u003E uraemia\u003C/strong\u003E. This is especially given the history of end stage renal disease with consideration of haemodialysis indicating severe disease. This is further supported by the biochemistry results and accompanying symptoms of nausea and vomiting. Furthermore, uraemic pericarditis often, but not always, presents without fever, whereas fever may be seen more commonly in infective aetiologies. In this case, his fever is borderline.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute coronary syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (ACS) is a common precipitant for acute pericarditis. However, the patient has not demonstrated any typical symptoms of ACS and has no history of previous episodes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntiarrhythmic medications\u003C/strong\u003E are not known to precipitate acute pericarditis. Medications associated with pericardial disease includes:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProcainamide\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPenicillins\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESome chemotherapy agents\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EViral infection\u003C/strong\u003E is a likely cause of acute pericarditis. However, there is more evidence for uraemic pericarditis in this presentation despite the one-week history of coryzal symptoms. If the patient was already on dialysis and his biochemistry was normal the likely aetiology would be viral infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBacterial pneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E is not supported as a diagnosis due to the lack of pulmonary signs.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Uraemia is a common cause of acute pericarditis in patients with severe renal disease."],"references":["Imazio M, Gaita F, LeWinter M. Evaluation and Treatment of Pericarditis A Systematic Review JAMA 2015; 314:1498-1506."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38160"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"50"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17600"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17600","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17600"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cbc179c2-80f7-4fb3-be85-48ecae1f998d.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cbc179c2-80f7-4fb3-be85-48ecae1f998d.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":698,"height":376}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38160","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38160"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-09T20:20:35+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-09T20:21:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"50"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52779"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","syn